Introduction

There is much medical research claimed that diabetes and hypertension are associate with each other. Moreover, some of the studies said that diabetes is the main factor for developing hypertension. The author curious whether this claim is valid for US citizens or not. Hence, this analysiss primary question is that For the US people, Does diabetes affect the prevalence of hypertension? In addition, the author wants to know whether this claim holds for each level of the aspects or not. Three aspects arouse the authors interests are gender, age, and obesity. (91 words)

The method used in this analysis is the Odd Ratios, retrieving from the logistic regression. The author decided to create two models for this analysis; both of them used hypertension status as a response variable. (31 words)

Data and Method

The data used in this analysis is provided by the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES). The author decides to use the data between the year 2011 to 2018. (30 words)

According to the data, some respondents were collected the blood pressure data more than once. The author decided to use the latest record for each respondent. After filtering out the respondent who does not have the blood pressure data and the error in the data, the records with systolic less than 60 mmHG and/or diastolic should higher than 40 mmHG, the author classified the data into two groups: normal and hypertension. (71 words)

Apart from the blood pressure, the author will use only the respondent whose age is not less than 18 years old at least 18 years old as both hypertension and diabetes might not be detected precisely in children. Furthermore, the author divided the citizen into three groups: adults, middle-aged, and seniors. (51 words)

For the obesity status, the Body Mass Index was used to cluster the respondent into two groups. The one who has BMI not less than 30 was considered obese; otherwise, he was considered no obese. (30 words)

The method used in this analysis is logistic regression. Two models were constructed in this analysis: the overall model and the model with the interested aspects. For both models, hypertension will be used as a response variable. In addition, the author let no hypertension as a reference level. The models coefficient can be used as the log of the odds ratios explaining the chance of being suffered from hypertension. (69 words)

Result

The data in this analysis contained the record of 20,711 people. The figure below will show the number of respondents for each level of hypertension and diabetes. (27 words)

Figure 1: The bar plot showing the number of respondents in each group and the corresponding percentage.

According to figure 1, 40.27% of the respondent were suffering from hypertension. Besides, 13.38% of the respondent had diabetes. When focusing on each group of diabetes, there is a difference between the group of hypertension. The people with diabetes had a higher chance of suffering from hypertension; however, the inverse trend appears in the people who did not have diabetes. (60 words)

Apart from the plot above, the author also considered the effect of diabetes on hypertension for each variable, which are gender, obesity, and age group. (25 words)

Figure 2: The bar plot showing the percentage classified by hypertension, diabetes, and another aspect.

According to figure 2, most groups had a different trend from the overall level; those who did not have diabetes had a lower chance of suffering from hypertension. The author noticed that classes that were different from the overall trends shared the typical result; those who belong to the specific class have a higher/lower chance of suffering from hypertension, regardless of diabetes. Those classes are male, obese, all classes from the age groups. (73 words)

To be more precise about the trend and result, two logistic models were constructed. The first model only used diabetes as a predictor. Another model used all variables as predictors. The result showed in table 3. (36 words)
